
Bits, bytes, and units
  1 bit (b) is a binary 0 or 1; 4 bits = nibble, 8 bits = 1 byte (B).
  Lowercase b = bits (used for transfer speed), uppercase B = bytes (used for storage).
  Magnitudes for bits: Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb (each step = ×1000).
  1000 bits = 1 Kb; 1 Kb = 1000 bits; 1 Mb = 1,000,000 bits; 1 Gb = 1,000,000,000 bits; 1 Tb = 1,000,000,000,000 bits.
  Convert bits to bytes: divide by 8 (example: 1000 bits = 125 bytes).
  1 MB (megabyte) is eight times larger (in bits) than 1 Mb (megabit).

Speed notation
  Bits per second notation: bps, Kbps, Mbps, Gbps, Tbps (lowercase b always).
  Example: 50 bits sent in 2 seconds = 25 bps (50 ÷ 2).
  Example to remember: 250 MB/s = 250 × 8 = 2000 Mb/s = 2 Gb/s (faster than 1 Gb/s).

